## 1. Individual and Household Actions

### 1.1 Transportation Choices

Transportation is a major contributor to air pollution, responsible for approximately 20-25% of global CO2 emissions ([Ramos, 2020](https://www.climatetracker.org/25-solutions-to-air-pollution/)). Individuals can significantly reduce their pollution footprint by adopting the following:

- **Use Public Transportation and Carpooling:** Increasing public transit ridership reduces the number of vehicles on roads, decreasing emissions. Carpooling similarly reduces per capita emissions ([Arcadia Power, 2017](https://blog.arcadia.com/25-impactful-ways-reduce-air-pollution/)).

- **Active Transport:** Walking and cycling produce zero emissions and provide health co-benefits. Cities with bike-share systems (e.g., Washington, DC) demonstrate successful adoption of cycling as eco-friendly transport ([Ramos, 2020](https://www.climatetracker.org/25-solutions-to-air-pollution/)).

- **Maintain Vehicles:** Regular vehicle maintenance, including tire inflation and engine tuning, improves fuel efficiency and reduces emissions by up to 10% ([Arcadia Power, 2017](https://blog.arcadia.com/25-impactful-ways-reduce-air-pollution/)).

- **Choose Eco-Friendly Vehicles:** Transitioning to electric, hybrid, or biofuel-powered cars reduces emissions. Governments can support this through incentives and infrastructure such as EV charging stations ([NICE, 2017](https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng70)).

### 1.2 Energy Use at Home

Household energy consumption contributes significantly to air pollution, especially when reliant on fossil fuels.

- **Energy Conservation:** Simple habits like turning off unused lights, using energy-efficient bulbs (LEDs), and insulating homes reduce electricity demand, thereby lowering emissions from power plants ([Arcadia Power, 2017](https://blog.arcadia.com/25-impactful-ways-reduce-air-pollution/)).

- **Efficient Appliances:** Purchasing ENERGY STAR-certified appliances can reduce energy use by 30%, saving approximately $575 annually and preventing 5,500 pounds of greenhouse gases per household ([Arcadia Power, 2017](https://blog.arcadia.com/25-impactful-ways-reduce-air-pollution/)).

- **Clean Cooking and Heating:** Switching from solid fuels (coal, wood) to clean fuels like electricity, natural gas, or LPG reduces indoor and outdoor pollution ([C40 Cities, n.d.](https://www.c40.org/other/clean-air-cities-declaration)).

- **Avoid Dryers:** Air-drying clothes reduces energy consumption and emissions ([Arcadia Power, 2017](https://blog.arcadia.com/25-impactful-ways-reduce-air-pollution/)).

### 1.3 Consumer Habits

- **Choose Low-VOC Products:** Volatile Organic Compounds (VOCs) from paints, cleaners, and personal care products contribute significantly to urban air pollution. Using low-VOC or water-based products reduces this source ([Fell, 2018](https://www.ucdavis.edu/news/consumer-industrial-products-overtake-transportation-source-urban-air-pollution)).

- **Reduce, Reuse, Recycle:** Minimizing waste reduces landfill emissions (methane) and energy used in production and transport ([EPA, n.d.](https://www.epa.gov/recycle/reducing-waste-what-you-can-do)).

- **Grow Food Locally:** Gardening reduces emissions from food transport and packaging ([Arcadia Power, 2017](https://blog.arcadia.com/25-impactful-ways-reduce-air-pollution/)).

