## 3. Government and Policy Interventions

### 3.1 Urban Planning and Clean Air Zones

- **Incorporate Air Quality in Planning:** Local governments should integrate air pollution considerations in urban development, avoiding siting vulnerable institutions near pollution hotspots ([NICE, 2017](https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng70)).

- **Clean Air Zones:** Implement zones with vehicle restrictions or charges targeting high-emission vehicles to reduce urban pollution ([NICE, 2017](https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng70)).

- **Promote Active and Public Transport:** Investing in cycling infrastructure, pedestrian-friendly design, and efficient public transit reduces reliance on private vehicles ([Sofia et al., 2020](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11356-020-08647-x)).

### 3.2 Emission Standards and Incentives

- **Vehicle Emission Regulations:** Strengthening standards for light and heavy-duty vehicles reduces pollutants ([UN Environment, 2018](https://wedocs.unep.org/handle/20.500.11822/25496)).

- **Subsidies and Scrappage Schemes:** Encouraging replacement of old, polluting vehicles with cleaner alternatives ([The Guardian, 2019](https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/may/17/how-you-and-your-government-can-tackle-air-pollution)).

- **Driver Training and Smooth Driving:** Programs to promote fuel-efficient driving reduce emissions and fuel consumption ([NICE, 2017](https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng70)).

### 3.3 Monitoring and Public Awareness

- **Air Quality Monitoring Networks:** Deploying real-time monitoring facilitates timely interventions and public information ([Sofia et al., 2020](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11356-020-08647-x)).

- **Public Information Campaigns:** Educating citizens on pollution sources, health impacts, and exposure reduction strategies improves community engagement ([NICE, 2017](https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng70)).

